Text Mining of Glassdoor Reviews

29 August 2021

1. Aim

The aim of this project is to classify the Glassdoor reviews of a company into various topics, and ascertain the topics that are of importance.

2. Activate Packages

The tidyverse, rvest and glue libraries are activated for Tidyverse approach of coding and web scraping respectively.

pacman::p_load(tidyverse, rvest, glue)

3. Collect reviews from Glassdoor

Out of the myraid of companies from Glassdoor, the pick is my current employer, Central Provident Fund Board. Data from 2016 onwards, i.e. 5 years worth of data shall be scraped. That adds up to 20 pages worth of review. A scraper function is being defined for this task.

scraping_function <- function(target_company, page_num)
{
  tryCatch({
    Sys.sleep(3)
    cat(glue::glue("Scraping page {page_num} ~ "))
    url <- glue("https://www.glassdoor.sg/Reviews/{target_company}P{page_num}.htm?sort.sortType=RD&sort.ascending=false&filter.iso3Language=eng")
    read_html(url) %>% 
      html_nodes(".gdReview") %>% 
      html_text() %>% 
      str_match(., "Pros.+Helpful") %>% 
      as_tibble(., .name_repair = ~ "V1") %>% 
      mutate(V2 = str_match(V1, "Pros.+Cons")[ , 1],
             V3 = str_match(V1, "Cons.+Be the first")[ , 1],
             pros = sub(".*Pros", "", V2),
             pros = sub("Cons.*", "", pros),
             cons = sub(".*Cons", "", V3),
             cons = sub("Be.*", "", cons)
      ) %>% 
      select(pros, cons) %>% 
      rowid_to_column("id") %>% 
      drop_na()},
    error = function(e){cat("Error in scraping: ",
                            conditionMessage(e), "\n")})
}

An empty dataframe review_all is initialized to store all the reviews that are scraped.

review_all = data.frame()[ , ]

For loop is then written to commence the scraping process.

for (i in seq(1,20,1)) {

  review_all <- bind_rows(review_all, review)
}

4. Topic Modeling with tm library

Next, the libraries tm and textclean are activated. The tm library is used to construct a document-term matrix which describes the frequency of terms that occur in a collection of document. In this project, each row stands for a review and each column refers to the word. The values within the matrix are the frequencies of the word. The textclean library is required for pre-processing and cleaning of text.

pacman::p_load(tm, textclean)

Next step is to clean, prepare the text and create the document-term matrix. A function is defined for this task.

text_cleaning_function <- function(the_text) {
  
  the_text <- as.character(the_text)
  
  the_text <- the_text %>% 
    str_remove_all(pattern = "[^\\s]*[0-9][^\\s]*") %>% # remove words that comprise of numeric characters
    stringr::str_remove_all(pattern = "[[:punct:]]") %>% # remove all punctiations
    stringr::str_remove_all(pattern = "Continue reading") %>% # remove "Continue Reading" which was extracted together 
    stringr::str_trim() %>%
    stringr::str_squish() %>%
    textclean::replace_number(remove = T) %>% 
    textclean::replace_date(replacement = "") %>% 
    textclean::replace_time(replacement = "") %>% 
    textclean::replace_hash(replacement = "") %>% 
    textclean::replace_contraction() %>% 
    textclean::replace_word_elongation() %>% 
    textclean::replace_emoji() %>% 
    textclean::replace_emoticon() %>% 
    textclean::replace_internet_slang()
  
  the_text_dtm <-
    tm::VCorpus(VectorSource(the_text)) %>%
    tm::tm_map(removeWords, stopwords("en"))
  
  return(tm::DocumentTermMatrix(the_text_dtm))
  
  }

Call on the function to create the document-term matrix for the pros and cons reviews respectively.

dtm_pros <- text_cleaning_function(review_all %>% select(pros) %>% drop_na())
dtm_cons <- text_cleaning_function(review_all %>% select(cons) %>% drop_na())

Extracting the terms that appear at least 6 times.

freqterm_pros <- tm::findFreqTerms(dtm_pros, 6)
freqterm_cons <- tm::findFreqTerms(dtm_cons, 6)

Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) is an approach used to fit topic models, where similar groups of items can be clustered together. k is set at 3 in this instance, in order to build 3 topics out of the text. In the later walk-through using textmineR, more topics will be defined for comparison and evaluation of the model.

pacman::p_load(topicmodels)
pros_lda3 <- topicmodels::LDA(dtm_pros, 
                              k = 3,
                              control = list(seed = 082401))

cons_lda3 <- topicmodels::LDA(dtm_cons, 
                              k = 3,
                              control = list(seed = 082402))

Let’s apply auto-tidy using tidy and input beta as argument in order to extract as per-topic-per-word probabilities. This is followed by the selecting the top 10 words per topic and visualizing them.

In summmary, under the analysis for pros review, topic 1 seems to suggest a good environment and pay. Topic 2 implies that colleagues are helpful, friendly and nice, and topic 3 seems to be work life balance and nice people or environment.

As for cons review, topic 1 seems to suggest a topic regarding time and progression, and couldn’t really make out topic 2. Topic 3 seems to be a theme on how busy the employees are.

However, the probabilities are not conclusive in terms of the topics which are more significant than others. This will be further analyzed in the next segment using the textmineR library, where the model evaluation will be covered.

5. Topic Modeling with textmineR library

This is the more preferred approach to topic modeling. The textmineR library is first activated. A new function text_cleaning_function_2 is defined for pre-processing of text.

text_cleaning_function_2 <- function(your_text) 
{
  your_text <- as.character(your_text)
  
  your_text <- your_text %>% 
    stringr::str_remove_all(pattern = "[^\\s]*[0-9][^\\s]*") %>%
    stringr::str_remove_all(pattern = "[[:punct:]]") %>% 
    stringr::str_remove_all(pattern = "Continue reading") %>% 
    stringr::str_trim() %>% 
    stringr::str_squish() %>% 
    textclean::replace_number(remove = T) %>% 
    textclean::replace_date(replacement = "") %>% 
    textclean::replace_time(replacement = "") %>% 
    textclean::replace_hash(replacement = "") %>% 
    textclean::replace_contraction() %>% 
    textclean::replace_word_elongation() %>% 
    textclean::replace_emoji() %>% 
    textclean::replace_emoticon() %>% 
    textclean::replace_internet_slang()
  
  return(as.data.frame(your_text))
}

The data under the review_all dataframe are then pre-processed using text_cleaning_function_2 and stored under pros_cleaned and cons_cleaned.

pros_cleaned <- text_cleaning_function_2(review_all$pros) %>% rowid_to_column("id")
cons_cleaned <- text_cleaning_function_2(review_all$cons) %>% rowid_to_column("id")

Next step is to create the document-term matrix using the CreateDtm function within the textmineR library.

set.seed(082403)
dtm_pros_cleaned <- textmineR::CreateDtm(doc_vec = pros_cleaned$your_text,
                                         doc_names = pros_cleaned$id,
                                         ngram_window = c(1, 2),
                                         stopword_vec = stopwords("en"),
                                         verbose = F)

dtm_pros_cleaned <- dtm_pros_cleaned[ , colSums(dtm_pros_cleaned) > 2] # choosing words with frequency more than 2

set.seed(082404)
dtm_cons_cleaned <- textmineR::CreateDtm(doc_vec = cons_cleaned$your_text,
                                         doc_names = cons_cleaned$id,
                                         ngram_window = c(1, 2),
                                         stopword_vec = stopwords("en"),
                                         verbose = F)


dtm_cons_cleaned <- dtm_cons_cleaned[ , colSums(dtm_cons_cleaned) > 2] # choosing words with frequency more than 2

Fitting the LDA model using textmineR. For this we will select 12 topics for a more effective comparison of the various topics in the subsequent segments.

set.seed(082405)
lda_model_pros_cleaned <- textmineR::FitLdaModel(dtm = dtm_pros_cleaned,
                                                 k = 12,
                                                 iterations = 500,
                                                 burnin = 200,
                                                 alpha = 0.1,
                                                 beta = 0.05,
                                                 optimize_alpha = T,
                                                 calc_likelihood = T,
                                                 calc_r2 = T,
                                                 calc_coherence = T)

                                                 alpha = 0.1,
                                                 beta = 0.05,
                                                 optimize_alpha = T,

6. Model Evaluation

To evaluate the overall goodness of fit, the textmineR has features to extract the R-squared, log likelihood and phi. The models will also be evaluated using coherence and prevalence.

R-squared

R-squared is interpreted as the proportion of variability in the data explained by the model, as with linear regression.

lda_model_pros_cleaned$r2 # for pros
## [1] 0.3745076

This implies that the results of the LDA model for pros review explains 37% of its variability.

lda_model_cons_cleaned$r2 # for cons
## [1] 0.3053422

This implies that the results of the LDA model for cons review explains 30% of its variablity.

Likelihood

plot(lda_model_pros_cleaned$log_likelihood,
     type = "l") # for pros

plot(lda_model_pros_cleaned$log_likelihood,
     type = "l") # for cons

Phi

Top 10 terms with the highest phi for each topic are extracted.phi represents a distribution of words over topics.

lda_model_pros_cleaned$top_terms <- textmineR::GetTopTerms(phi = lda_model_pros_cleaned$phi,
                                                           M = 10)

Prevalence

Prevalence values are also another area which is used to measure the quality of models.Prevalence provides the most frequent topics within the corpus.

lda_model_pros_cleaned$prevalence <- 
  colSums(lda_model_pros_cleaned$theta / sum(lda_model_pros_cleaned$theta )* 100)

lda_model_pros_cleaned$prevalence # for pros
##       t_1       t_2       t_3       t_4       t_5       t_6       t_7       t_8 
##  5.879958  5.547511  4.399059  6.667683  7.555691  8.328231 11.029043  8.776881 
##       t_9      t_10      t_11      t_12 
## 10.859315 10.778976  8.643337 11.534315
lda_model_pros_cleaned$summary <- 
  data.frame(topic = rownames(lda_model_pros_cleaned$phi),
             coherence = round(lda_model_pros_cleaned$coherence, 2),
             prevalence = round(lda_model_pros_cleaned$prevalence, 2),
             top_terms = apply(lda_model_pros_cleaned$top_terms, 2, function(x){paste(x, collapse= ", ")})) # for pros
lda_model_cons_cleaned$prevalence <- 
  colSums(lda_model_cons_cleaned$theta / sum(lda_model_cons_cleaned$theta )* 100)

9. Summary

To conclude, it can be deduced that the main pros of working at CPF Board are that colleagues are very willing to teach, as seen under topic 8. As for the cons, the main grouses are reflected under topic 6 which contain keywords such as balance, customer and degree, suggesting these comments may be made by employees who are working closely with customers.
